<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B228D56FF06442DA716F8B5" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B228D56FF06442DA308F9A6" blockId="8.[189,310,1577,1603]" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">
<heading id="43363C057B228D56FF06442DA308F9A6" bold="true" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FF06442DA308F9A6" bold="true" box="[189,310,1577,1603]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B228D56FF06445EA716F8B5" blockId="8.[188,1399,1626,1873]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">
The frons sparsely punctate, with variable interspaces among coarse punctures, is a distinctive character for this species; on other examined 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B228D56FDE6447BA11DF97C" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1978" box="[605,803,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FDE6447BA11DF97C" box="[605,803,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">Austrosphecodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the frons is densely punctate, except near antennal alveoli. The two known females have only two submarginal cells, with a vestige of 1 r-m in the 
<typeStatus id="C77A35CB7B228D56FAAB44A7A749F958" box="[1296,1399,1699,1725]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">holotype</typeStatus>
left fore wing. Its females have the T1 mostly impunctate and the anterior surface of the mesoscutum rugulose by crowded punctures, a combination only otherwise found in 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B228D56FBFB44E9A6D3F8E2" baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1088,1261,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FBFB44E9A66CF8E2" box="[1088,1106,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FBDD44E9A6D3F8E2" box="[1126,1261,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The body length of more than 
<quantity id="DF39268C7B228D56FE014516A03BF8C9" box="[442,517,1810,1836]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
, the mesoscutum disc sparsely punctate and polished, and the scutellum homogeneously rugose easily separate 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B228D56FD3C4533A0CAF8B5" authority="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira, 2022" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Pereira" authorityYear="2022" box="[647,756,1846,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balrog" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FD3C4533A0A7F8B4" box="[647,665,1847,1873]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FD1C4532A0CAF8B5" box="[679,756,1846,1872]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">balrog</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3186EA007B228D56FD474533A168F8B4" box="[764,854,1847,1873]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from 
<taxonomicName id="DFC1F0EA7B228D56FC254533A67BF8B5" baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[926,1093,1846,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Austrosphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FC254533A18EF8B4" box="[926,944,1847,1873]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FC054532A67BF8B5" box="[958,1093,1846,1872]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="50DBD8E27B228D56FF06457EA0C5F80D" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="187E8B697B228D56FF06457EA37AF871" blockId="8.[189,324,1914,1940]" box="[189,324,1914,1940]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">
<heading id="43363C057B228D56FF06457EA37AF871" bold="true" box="[189,324,1914,1940]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="63" reason="3">
<emphasis id="2AB5577B7B228D56FF06457EA37AF871" bold="true" box="[189,324,1914,1940]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="187E8B697B228D56FF0645AEA0C5F80D" blockId="8.[189,1399,1961,2025]" pageId="8" pageNumber="63">A tall and menacing being who can shroud itself in fire, darkness, and shadow, created by J.R.R. Tolkien. The name is used as a proper noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
